00:29:59.000 --> 00:30:01.000
Hampstead, wasn't it?

171
00:30:01.000 --> 00:30:05.000
Can't remember the year, maybe 1985, I think.

172
00:30:05.000 --> 00:30:14.000
And during the puja, she said, now the ladies who have never done a puja to me, they can come to the stage and do it.

173
00:30:14.000 --> 00:30:20.000
And two ladies came, you know, dressed in jeans.

174
00:30:20.000 --> 00:30:23.000
They were wearing jeans, you know, they're not wearing a sari.

175
00:30:23.000 --> 00:30:26.000
And mother said, that's not possible, you know.

176
00:30:26.000 --> 00:30:33.000
Someone should have given them saris or taught them how to wear a sari.

177
00:30:33.000 --> 00:30:39.000
It's not hard to find a sari in England, you know, because there are so many people from India, in England, you know.

178
00:30:39.000 --> 00:30:44.000
And someone was saying, really in future, make sure you teach all the new people.

179
00:30:44.000 --> 00:30:49.000
If they come to a puja, they should, the ladies especially, they must wear a sari.

180
00:30:49.000 --> 00:30:55.000
And the gentleman also must wear this Indian Curtis, you know.

181
00:30:56.000 --> 00:31:08.000
And strangely enough, at this one set of tours, I was there with Carol and she said, now on the way back, you know, back to London, back to your countries,

182
00:31:08.000 --> 00:31:16.000
especially the English going on the British Airways, that's their line used to be called the British Airways.

183
00:31:16.000 --> 00:31:22.000
Make sure you wear your saris and your duties.

184
00:31:22.000 --> 00:31:32.000
Mother said, wear your duties, wear your saris, wear your pajama curtis and don't forget to wear also the red dot on the forehead, you know, the tikka.

185
00:31:32.000 --> 00:31:35.000
So we did that because mother told us to do.

186
00:31:35.000 --> 00:31:41.000
And then when you always, she also said, and when you go to work or when you go shopping, you know,

187
00:31:41.000 --> 00:31:49.000
don't be afraid to wear the saris and to wear the pajama curtis, you know, just enjoy and wear the red dot on the forehead as well.

188
00:31:49.000 --> 00:31:50.000
So we did.

189
00:31:50.000 --> 00:31:56.000
As we arrived in London, you know, there was some saja yogis there to collect us, you know,

190
00:31:56.000 --> 00:32:04.000
and they saw us coming of our flight all dressed up like that and they said, oh my God, have you gone mad or what?

191
00:32:04.000 --> 00:32:10.000
You know, this is not allowed because are you behaving like the Hare Krishna people or what?

192
00:32:10.000 --> 00:32:17.000
You know, this is not to be done, you know, but they didn't know.

193
00:32:17.000 --> 00:32:21.000
Well, mother told us to do that, you know, not just today, but whenever we want.

194
00:32:21.000 --> 00:32:26.000
And some people were saying, oh my goodness, this is the end of Sahaja Yoga now.

195
00:32:26.000 --> 00:32:29.000
This will definitely be the end of Sahaja Yoga.

196
00:32:29.000 --> 00:32:32.000
But Sahaja Yoga did not die really.

197
00:32:32.000 --> 00:32:40.000
Some of us wore our whites, you know, I remember once going out shopping and I was going in my whites, you know,

198
00:32:40.000 --> 00:32:49.000
and someone came to talk to me, oh, you must be a baker because I was dressed completely in white with a little white hat, you know, and the red dot.

199
00:32:49.000 --> 00:32:52.000
And they said, you must be a baker, you know, I'm sorry.

200
00:32:52.000 --> 00:32:57.000
I mean, I'm not a baker, but I have a photograph of this lady Shrimant.

201
00:32:57.000 --> 00:33:08.000
We talked about Sahaja and we laughed a lot, you know, you know, it's a really strange thing to be confused with the bakers because all in white, you know, those whites, you know,

202
00:33:08.000 --> 00:33:18.000
Caro also went to for a job interview wearing a sari, you know, she didn't get the job, but she knew she wasn't going to get the job in any case.

203
00:33:18.000 --> 00:33:20.000
She was not qualified for that job.

204
00:33:20.000 --> 00:33:32.000
She was going just for practice interview to practice for another interview where she thought she had a better chance, you know, but she even went for a job interview wearing a sari.

205
00:33:32.000 --> 00:33:34.000
So many Sahaja Yogis did that.

206
00:33:34.000 --> 00:33:35.000
Nothing happened really.

207
00:33:35.000 --> 00:33:36.000
There was no problem.

208
00:33:36.000 --> 00:33:47.000
You know, people are not afraid of the saris, you know, there were occasions where Caro went to, we went to the airport because mother was coming or going.

209
00:33:47.000 --> 00:33:58.000
And on those on a few occasions, Caro decided to wear a sari to go and see Maduretti Airport and some.

210
00:33:58.000 --> 00:34:10.000
Some English Sahaja Yoginis were telling telling her, you know, if she don't currently, you know, you must be a little bit crazy to come dressed in a sari because this is an airport.

211
00:34:10.000 --> 00:34:16.000
And as you can see, no one else is doing that except maybe one or two Indian Sahaja Yoginis who lived in England.

212
00:34:16.000 --> 00:34:35.000
So, you know, that's really are you not worried that mother might tell you off or something and kind of felt, no, I don't see why, you know, and the fact the mother was very pleased that she came dressed in a sari and spoke to her, you know, and everything went beautifully.

213
00:34:35.000 --> 00:34:38.000
Mother was not at all displeased on the contrary.

214
00:34:38.000 --> 00:34:46.000
And she did that a few more times and still other people who didn't know came to tell her, Caro, are you going bonkers or what?

215
00:34:46.000 --> 00:34:47.000
Coming dressed with a sari.

216
00:34:47.000 --> 00:34:48.000
This is not the push.

217
00:34:48.000 --> 00:34:49.000
Are you getting confused?

218
00:34:49.000 --> 00:34:53.000
This is the airport, you know, and she did a few times really.

219
00:34:53.000 --> 00:35:02.000
So there was a certain fear of this type of clothes, you know, but there's something very special.

220
00:35:02.000 --> 00:35:05.000
Mother kept explaining these things to everybody.

221
00:35:05.000 --> 00:35:11.000
So one day I came all the way from Portugal, especially to meet Shri Mataji.

222
00:35:11.000 --> 00:35:29.000
And I had been in London maybe about three weeks, I think, waiting for a chance to see mother really if there's a chance, if mother gives a public program or a push or an invitation of some kind, I was staying staying at maybe mother might come to the ashram at Chelsea Road, you know, this was 1983.

223
00:35:29.000 --> 00:35:57.000
So I was waiting for a chance and then an invitation came mother is going to see a sari fashion show, you know, everybody's welcome, you know, so to see a, you know, a show of saris, you know, where the some ladies come from India, and they know how to model the saris and display the saris and show them and mother went to see that and told us invited everybody come and see the message came rather late.

224
00:35:57.000 --> 00:36:10.000
When you got the message, so you knew we cannot arrive on time. It's impossible. Although you're running all the way to the tube and after the tube, you were running all over the place trying to reach the place as early as possible.

225
00:36:10.000 --> 00:36:11.000
We were late, really.

226
00:36:11.000 --> 00:36:24.000
So when I arrived there at that center, it was a big exhibition about the products that I exported from India and the sari is a very important export from India, of course, all over the world.

227
00:36:25.000 --> 00:36:35.000
And so we couldn't find mother anywhere and you were running around that place with three different floors, you know, and we just couldn't find mother anyway.

228
00:36:35.000 --> 00:36:40.000
And in the end mother appeared that long after a long time and by then you were exhausted.

229
00:36:41.000 --> 00:36:45.000
And we asked mother, where were you? I didn't ask another sari yogi was with me.

230
00:36:46.000 --> 00:36:56.000
Where were you? We couldn't find you anywhere. Mother says, where else could I be? Watching the saris fashion show, there's really nothing else to see here.

231
00:36:56.000 --> 00:37:03.000
This is the most important thing. Make sure you don't miss seeing this because these ladies are so beautiful.

232
00:37:03.000 --> 00:37:10.000
We're modeling the saris so beautiful, so innocent, so sweet, so elegant, so dignified.

233
00:37:10.000 --> 00:37:18.000
What a beautiful thing you really should see this, you know, don't miss it because there was a show on the hour, every hour another show starts, you know.

234
00:37:19.000 --> 00:37:27.000
So at all times mother was showing tremendous respect for the saris and she herself enjoyed seeing people wearing saris also.

235
00:37:27.000 --> 00:37:37.000
And I've noticed that all saris yoginis are quite enthusiastic about seeing mother dressed in the sari, how well mother looks.

236
00:37:37.000 --> 00:37:43.000
Sometimes we are watching a video at home, me and Carl and Carl said, can you rewind the beginning?

237
00:37:43.000 --> 00:37:49.000
She wants to see mother entering on the stage, wearing a beautiful sari. Sometimes it's just a white sari even.

238
00:37:49.000 --> 00:37:55.000
And oh, how beautiful. Can you rewind again? I want to see mother coming, you know, and mother comes dressed in that sari.

239
00:37:55.000 --> 00:38:00.000
It's something, it's like a vision of a God that's coming onto the stage. Everybody feels that.

240
00:38:01.000 --> 00:38:11.000
So saja yoginis are very enthusiastic about mother and her saris, but mother is also appreciative of when the saja yoginis wear the saris.

241
00:38:11.000 --> 00:38:21.000
So on the Indian tour, we were there, you know, to get married again. Mother had already arranged our marriage and now we're going to get married in England first.

242
00:38:21.000 --> 00:38:25.000
And now mother told us to come to India to get a sahaja marriage as well.

243
00:38:26.000 --> 00:38:39.000
And then the message came mother is going to select the saris for the brides, you know, so gentlemen, please make sure you come, you know, and bring your wallets, you know, so it's your chance to buy the sari for your bride.

244
00:38:39.000 --> 00:38:45.000
You know, so everybody came to see mother buying the saris or choosing the saris for the brides.

245
00:38:46.000 --> 00:38:58.000
And the mother being such an expert on the saris, you know, there was a whole truck full of saris, you know, someone drove a full truck full of saris.

246
00:38:58.000 --> 00:39:01.000
It was thousands of saris there to choose from.

247
00:39:02.000 --> 00:39:13.000
And because mother is such an expert, mother went through the whole consignment of saris at fast speed, you know, fast, fast, fast, because she just knows, she doesn't even have to touch it.

248
00:39:13.000 --> 00:39:21.000
She knows immediately what is a good sari, what's not a good sari and sometimes she would approve a sari.

249
00:39:21.000 --> 00:39:25.000
Most of them should reject and then she would touch it and see it and then check the price.

250
00:39:25.000 --> 00:39:29.000
If the price was not right, she would reject the sari straight away.

251
00:39:29.000 --> 00:39:42.000
So mother was careful to keep save our money as well, you know, so what took care and attention mother put into those saris and what expertise, how she could go through.

252
00:39:42.000 --> 00:39:48.000
Thousands of saris at such speed and then she created, it's quite complicated.

253
00:39:48.000 --> 00:39:51.000
She had several piles of saris she approved for the brides.

254
00:39:51.000 --> 00:39:56.000
There were three piles of, you know, lower price, medium price and more expensive.

255
00:39:57.000 --> 00:40:03.000
Then there was a pile of saris for people who want to buy a really expensive sari to take home for their mothers or for their aunt.

256
00:40:03.000 --> 00:40:05.000
So it's a very, very special gift.

257
00:40:06.000 --> 00:40:20.000
Then there were other piles of saris for daily use during the tour, you know, so simple, you know, and then another pile of saris for going to pushes or going to programs during the tour for those who need.

258
00:40:21.000 --> 00:40:26.000
So what a complex thing, mother was dealing with so many piles of saris, but she's a top expert.

259
00:40:26.000 --> 00:40:32.000
She knew more about it than the man was selling the saris, you know, it was incredible.

260
00:40:35.000 --> 00:40:42.000
Let's see. Oh, yes. One day at mother's house, I happened to be the only saja yogi there and another one.

261
00:40:42.000 --> 00:40:57.000
So there was two of us and that day mother had to go to a very important diplomatic conference and mother had a domestic assistant who was a man, really a young man like us, our same age as us, but it's a man really.

262
00:40:58.000 --> 00:41:04.000
And he was in charge of ironing mother's saris, you know, because he was doing all the domestic assistance and cooking as well.

263
00:41:05.000 --> 00:41:13.000
And we had seen him ironing mother's saris sometimes, you know, because we were dead on the basement sometimes and that's the place where he used to do it.

264
00:41:13.000 --> 00:41:31.000
So we had seen him doing, but we didn't know how to iron a sari, but that day was ill, you know, so mother looked at us and the time was ticking now, so she'd be coming at any moment, you know, to pick her up with the limousine to that special, very special event, you know.

265
00:41:32.000 --> 00:41:39.000
And so mother looked at us and said, can you iron me a sari? You said, of course, mother, no problem. You know, full of confidence.

266
00:41:42.000 --> 00:41:51.000
The problem is that none of us have ever ironed the saris. And this was a very special sari for a very important event, you know, in the evening.

267
00:41:51.000 --> 00:41:57.000
So we knew this is quite a rather very special sari, very expensive as well.

268
00:41:57.000 --> 00:42:05.000
It would be a big shame if you burn this sari or do a really bad job and put wrinkles on the sari and spoil the whole thing, you know.

269
00:42:05.000 --> 00:42:20.000
But we asked mother to help, although mother wasn't there. She was upstairs in the rooms and the sari got ironed, you know, and on this occasion, we really, you know, got to see the sari.

270
00:42:21.000 --> 00:42:32.000
And in great detail and the patterns and everything, quite very interesting, you know, usually we don't notice in such great detail, but ironing the sari gave that experience.

271
00:42:32.000 --> 00:42:49.000
But we noticed we were really getting thoughtless while ironing the sari. It was a special experience, you know, something I only did once in my life, but it felt special really to pass the test because there was a good chance we burn the sari or make a mess of it.

272
00:42:49.000 --> 00:42:55.000
But everything went well. Mother was guiding us and helping us. And then mother wore the sari.

273
00:42:55.000 --> 00:43:04.000
And we may not notice so much when mother is wearing a sari, you know, because we are talking to her and we forget to look at the sari even sometimes.

274
00:43:04.000 --> 00:43:13.000
But on that occasion, we really saw the sari, you know, how amazing mother looked in that special sari for going out for a special diplomatic conference.

275
00:43:13.000 --> 00:43:26.000
And my wife, Carol, she used to complain sometimes when I come, having seen mother, you know, then she wants to know everything mother said or what happened, what people are doing and saying.

276
00:43:26.000 --> 00:43:32.000
And I used to try and remember everything mother said and people said and what was happening to tell her everything in great detail.

277
00:43:32.000 --> 00:43:37.000
Next day, she would ask me to tell the same story again and the next day and the next day.

278
00:43:37.000 --> 00:43:47.000
This actually helps me to remember things sometimes. But the first thing Carol always asked me is what was the color of the sari, you know, mother was wearing it.

279
00:43:47.000 --> 00:43:57.000
Oh, I don't know. I didn't see. What a disaster. I forgot to see the color of the sari mother was wearing.

280
00:43:57.000 --> 00:44:10.000
And Carol used to be, oh my God, you didn't see the color of the sari, but you know, don't do this to me, please. Next time, at least know that at least tell me the color of the sari, you know, minimum, if not a bit more detail, you know.

281
00:44:10.000 --> 00:44:19.000
All right. So that's the one time I was able to describe the sari very in great detail because we are in that sari and we saw mother wearing it straight away.

282
00:44:19.000 --> 00:44:37.000
So we could not fail to notice that. So that was an interesting event, but a lot happened in that event because then when mother ultimately, you know, mother went down the steps, you know, and this mother was going down the steps wearing that sari.

283
00:44:37.000 --> 00:44:54.000
I got the kind of a vision, you know, that mother was gliding on a cloud, you know, like a divine, you know, which she is of course, but usually you see mother more as a human person, you know, but she seemed to be gliding on a cloud going down the stairs, going into the car.

284
00:44:55.000 --> 00:45:07.000
And that was an incredible vision, you know, a special moment that still today I remember because usually we don't get this type of feeling, you know, it's, you know, we're in the present, there's no vision is that's what it is.

285
00:45:07.000 --> 00:45:15.000
But the whole sari event seemed to have had an effect on us. We felt very thoughtless whilst while ironing it, ironing it.

286
00:45:15.000 --> 00:45:28.000
And then when mother went and left the home, you know, it was like a divine vision, seeing mother gliding down the stairs as if she was going on a cloud almost, but that's just me trying to put it into words that feeling.

